(199, 1, '2014-07-28 18:07:02', '2014-07-28 18:07:02', '<p>The Corps Member Education Foundation supports educational opportunities for students of Teach For America corps members. The reality is that in our country where a child is born strongly predicts his or her educational outcomes and life prospects. The Corps Member Education Foundation was established by Teach For America alumni who witnessed that when provided the opportunity for an excellent education, students growing up in low-income communities can and will achieve.</p>\n<p> We also struggled with the lack of co-curricular opportunities and experiential learning opportunities many students growing up in high-income communities often take for granted: field trips, attending camps, etc. To offer students a high quality education in the classroom leaves teachers very little time to plan these co-curricular activities (not to mention raise the funds that otherwise would not be available).</p>\n<p>The Corps Member Education Foundation helps fill this void. We provide Teach For America corps members and alumni with tools and resources to initiate programs to increase the number of educational opportunities for students living in regions where Teach For America places corps members. In addition to providing corps members the opportunity to fund-raise, we provide project timelines, templates, and other tools that reduce the time necessary to plan their co-curricular activities. We also help reconnect alumni, many of whom moved away from their placement region after completing their Teach For America commitment, with their students and their placement communities.</p>\n<p><strong>Our Mission</strong></p>\n<p>Our mission is to support the movement to eliminate educational inequity by providing Teach For America corps members tools to enable these exceptional individuals to go beyond the classroom walls and their two year Teach For America commitment and provide the even more educational opportunities for their students.<br /><br />We provide the training and ongoing support necessary to ensure their success as teachers in low-income communities.<br /><br />Our teachers, also called corps members, go above and beyond traditional expectations to lead their students to significant academic achievement, despite the challenges of poverty and the limited capacity of the school system. In succeeding with their students, corps members show that students in low-income communities can achieve at high levels, offering further evidence that educational inequity is a solvable problem.<br /><br />Yet we know that enlisting additional high-quality teachers is not the ultimate solution. We believe that the best hope for ending educational inequity is to build a massive force of leaders in all fields who have the perspective and conviction that come from teaching successfully in low-income communities.<br /><br />During their two-year commitments, Teach For America corps members see firsthand that educational inequity is solvable and gain a grounded understanding of how to solve it.</p>\n<p>Beyond these two years, Teach For America alumni bring strong leadership to all levels of the school system and every professional sector, addressing the extra challenges facing children growing up in low-income communities, building the capacity of schools and districts, and changing the prevailing ideology through their examples and advocacy.</p>', 'What We Do', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-we-do', '', '', '2014-08-01 16:21:18', '2014-08-01 16:21:18', '', 197, 'http://dev.pica.is/cmef/?page_id=199', 1, 'page', '', 0),
